<para>
  The isotropic large strain elasticity &property; specifies that the
  <xref linkend="Flux-Stress"/> depends
  <emphasis>nonlinearly</emphasis> on the gradients of the <xref
  linkend="Field-Displacement"/>, <inlineequation><alt
  role="tex">\(u\)</alt></inlineequation>:
  <equation>
    <alt role="tex">
      \[ \sigma_{ij} = C_{ijkl}\epsilon_{kl} \]
    </alt>
  </equation>
  where <inlineequation><alt
  role="tex">\(\sigma_{ij}\)</alt></inlineequation> is the <xref
  linkend="Flux-Stress"/>, <inlineequation><alt
  role="tex">\(C_{ijkl}\)</alt></inlineequation> is an isotropic
  fourth rank tensor given by the modulus <varname>cijkl</varname>,
  and <inlineequation><alt
  role="tex">\(\epsilon\)</alt></inlineequation> is the nonlinear
  geometric strain,
  <equation id="Equation-nonlinear-strain">
    <alt role="tex">
      \[ \epsilon_{ij} = \frac12\left(
      \frac{\partial u_i}{\partial x_j}
      + \frac{\partial u_j}{\partial x_i}
      + \frac{\partial u_k}{\partial x_i}\frac{\partial u_k}{\partial x_j}
      \right). \]
    </alt>
  </equation>
  This form of the geometric strain is invariant under rigid
  rotations, unlike its linear variant, Eq.&nbsp;<xref
  linkend="Eqn-linear-strain"/>.
</para>
  

